1️⃣ Task Target (target object):-
Task ka target jo object task operate karta hai usko represent karta hai. Ye generally ye types ho sakte hain:-
Target Object	                        Description
WorkflowCase--------------Task agar workflow ke context me run ho raha ho
Custom Object-------------Koi bhi custom defined object jo task me use ho

Identity – Kisi user/employee account ka object
Example: Onboarding, Deprovisioning, Access Review

Application – System/application jiske upar task run hota hai
Example: Salesforce, Workday, Active Directory

Entitlement / Role / Group – Specific permissions, roles, or groups
Example: Admin Role, Finance Group

Policy – Identity / Access / Separation of Duty (SoD) Policy
Example: Violation check tasks

WorkflowCase – Workflow execution context object
Example: Approval workflow ke steps

Task / Job object – Kisi dusre task/job ko target karna
Example: Scheduled task to run another task

Population – Group of identities based on criteria
Example: All active employees in Finance

Report / ReportDefinition – Reporting tasks
Example: Access Review report generation

Rule / RuleContext – Rule execution target
Example: Identity validation or provisioning rules

AuditEvent / Event / Violation – Audit/Violation handling
Example: Compliance violation tasks

Certification / Review / Campaign – Access certification tasks
Example: Identity review campaigns

Custom Object – Organization-specific objects
Example: Custom table/object in SailPoint schema

Example:-
Target = Identity("John Doe")
Target = Application("Salesforce")

2️⃣ Task Target Type (getTargetType()):-
Ye target object ka type string me representation hai:-
Target Object	       TargetType Value
Identity	             "Identity"
Application	            "Application"
Entitlement	             "Entitlement"
Policy	                "Policy"
WorkflowCase	       "WorkflowCase"
Custom Object	       "CustomObject"
Ye basically instanceof check ke through return hota hai.

3️⃣ Task Execution Result (getExecutionResult()):-
Ye task ke execution ka output/result hota hai. Common values:-
Result Value	Description
"Success"	Task successfully complete hua
"Failure"	Task execution me error aaya
"Partial Success"	Task ka kuch part successfully run hua, kuch fail
"Skipped"	Task kisi condition ke wajah se skip hua
"Cancelled"	Task execution ko cancel kar diya gaya
"Unknown"	Result abhi set nahi hua.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
()Properties of Custom Objects:-

Dynamic Schema:-
Tu XML ya UI me define karta hai ki kaunse fields honge.
Example: badgeNumber, issueDate, departmentId

Integration with Tasks:-
Task ka target object custom object bhi ho sakta hai.
Example: Task run karo aur ProjectAccess object me check karo ki kaunse employees ko access update karna hai.

GetTargetType():-
getTargetType() return karega "CustomObject" ya custom name jo tu define karega.

Use in Rules & Workflows:-
Custom objects ko rules, workflows, aur provisioning tasks me target ke roop me use kar sakte ho.

Custom Object kya hai?
Definition: SailPoint me “Custom Object” basically aapke organization ka custom data structure ya object hai,
jo built-in SailPoint objects (jaise Identity, Application, Policy) me se nahi hai.
Ye object specific business requirement ke liye create hota hai.
Example use cases:-
Custom Object	              Purpose
EmployeeBadge	Organization ke employee badges ka info store karne ke liye
ProjectAccess	Kisi project ke liye special access record
DepartmentInfo	Custom department-specific data

class CustomObject {
    private String name;
    private String description;

    public CustomObject(String name, String desc) {
        this.name = name;
        this.description = desc;
    }

    public String getName() { return name; }
    public String getDescription() { return description; }
}

class Task {
    private Object target;

    public void setTarget(Object target) { this.target = target; }
    public Object getTarget() { return target; }

    public String getTargetType() {
        if(target instanceof CustomObject) return "CustomObject";
        return "Unknown";
    }

    public String getTargetName() {
        if(target instanceof CustomObject) return ((CustomObject)target).getName();
        return "Unknown";
    }
}

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        CustomObject myCustom = new CustomObject("ProjectAccess", "Custom project access data");
        Task t = new Task();
        t.setTarget(myCustom);

        System.out.println("Target Name: " + t.getTargetName());
        System.out.println("Target Type: " + t.getTargetType());
    }
}
Output:-
Target Name: ProjectAccess
Target Type: CustomObject
////////////////////////////*
()1️⃣ instanceof:-
Kya hai: Java ka ek keyword jo check karta hai ki koi object specific class ka instance hai ya nahi.

Syntax:-
if (object instanceof ClassName) { 
    // code
}
Example:-
Object obj = "Hello World";

if(obj instanceof String) {
    System.out.println("obj is a String!");
} else {
    System.out.println("obj is NOT a String!");
}
Output:-
obj is a String!
✅ Matlab instanceof se hum object ke type ko runtime pe check kar sakte hain.

2️⃣ (CustomObject) target → Type Casting:-
Kya hai: Agar hum sure hain ki target object actually CustomObject ka instance hai, toh hum usko explicitly CustomObject me cast karte hain.
Syntax:-
CustomObject co = (CustomObject) target;
Isse hum CustomObject ke methods aur fields use kar sakte hain.

()instanceof check karta hai ki kya target customobject ka object type hai ya nahi.

Ex:-
class CustomObject {
    private String name;

    public CustomObject(String name) { this.name = name; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
}

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Object target = new CustomObject("ProjectAccess");

        // Check type first
        if(target instanceof CustomObject) {
            CustomObject co = (CustomObject) target; // cast
            System.out.println("Target Name: " + co.getName());
        } else {
            System.out.println("Target is not a CustomObject");
        }
    }
}
Output:-
Target Name: ProjectAccess
///////*
()instanceof check karta hai ki kya target customobject ka object type hai ya nahi.
*//////
